title: Grateful Dead Live at Boston Garden on 1974-06-28
lineage: Dat (Sony PCM-R500) > Sound Devices 744T > Samplitude Professional v11.1 > FLAC/16
description: Set 1 Mississippi Half Step-> It Must Have Been The Roses-> Jack Straw, Beat It On Down The Line, Deal, Mexicali Blues, Tennessee Jed, Me And Bobby McGee, Loose Lucy, El Paso, Sugaree, Around & Around Set 2 Phil & Ned*, Sugar Magnolia-> Scarlet Begonias, Big River, To Lay Me Down, Me & My Uncle, Row Jimmy, Weather Report Suite Prelude-> Weather Report Suite Part 1-> Let It Grow-> Heaven Help The Fool Jam-> U.S. Blues-> Promised Land-> Goin' Down The Road Feelin' Bad-> Sunshine Daydream, E: Ship of Fools *Phil & Ned Between sets. This date is featured on Dick's Picks 12.

reviews.review_text:
Going Down the Road.. Oh my, This is really GOOD!
Half Step>Roses>Jack Straw
All three are excellent with the Jack Straw being very unique in texture coming out THE ROSES.
THE BIODTL is a Donna Jean feisty fiesta. 
You want strong independent female, Go DJG
Jerry's voice so sweet on Deal                                    and the band is sounding so KIND.
"A lifetime worth of the Mexicali Blues" 
Dig that BASS Heavy JED
"Bobby sang my Blues"-Garcia
The sound of time passing..
Sweet LUCY--How cool was it 
when they brought this one back! 
I WANT TO TURN UP MY DISCO
TO THE FULL WATTS TONIGHT.
El Paso--A tragic tale of lament and HOT LED.
and some blown lyrics. Regroup and RIDE!
A perfect place for SUGAREE
Around x2 is a strong set closer
(They sound just right 2-night)
Sugar Mag>Scarlet Yeah! The making of a future      new years eve just add FIRE!
Big River-Billy just tappin hard.
This tune certainly deserved
 it's 2nd Set status in 73/74
 Lay Me Down-anytime, anywhere
Can't say enough about this tune
JERRY's Vocals are mighty fine.
And Donna & Bobby alongside.
"Let the world go by
all lost and dreaming"
 Me & My Uncle-Weir can't resist
The Row Jimmy is the perfect set-up for WEATHER
WRS shines- not sure the entire jam should be labeled as part of the suite. 
So much territory explored after the 12 minute mark.
I like the way they regroup and head for U.S. Blues.           a tasty 'later in the set' Promised Land with a splice.    I would quibble with the 'U.S. Blues->Promised' because TO MY EARS  the band does not continue on from U.S. Blues into Promised. -there is just some noodling but no direct link between songs.
whatever the case Boston Gardens and the Dead in 74! 
GDTRFB is a good SPIRITUAL 
Thank You JESUS!
Ship of Fools is a rare encore 
and pretty heavy duty in that slot
kinda like a BABY BLUE.
Boston 74' This is a great example of what the Dead were doing in 74'.One hell of a show from one hell of a year.
